{"id":"2012.02163","submitter":"Jeremy Holt","authors":"Pengsheng Wen and Jeremy W. Holt","title":"Constraining the nonanalytic terms in the isospin-asymmetry expansion of\n  the nuclear equation of state","comments":"12 pages, 11 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. C 103, 064002 (2021)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevC.103.064002","report-no":null,"categories":"nucl-th","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  We examine the properties of the isospin-asymmetry expansion of the nuclear\nequation of state from chiral two- and three-body forces. We focus on\nextracting the high-order symmetry energy coefficients that consist of both\nnormal terms (occurring with even powers of the isospin asymmetry) as well as\nterms involving the logarithm of the isospin asymmetry that are formally\nnonanalytic around the expansion point of isospin-symmetric nuclear matter.\nThese coefficients are extracted from numerically precise perturbation theory\ncalculations of the equation of state coupled with a new set of finite\ndifference formulas that achieve stability by explicitly removing the effects\nof higher-order terms in the expansion. We consider contributions to the\nsymmetry energy coefficients from both two- and three-body interactions. It is\nfound that the coefficients of the logarithmic terms are generically larger in\nmagnitude than those of the normal terms from second-order perturbation theory\ndiagrams, but overall the normal terms give larger contributions to the ground\nstate energy. The high-order isospin-asymmetry terms are especially relevant at\nlarge densities where they affect the proton fraction in beta-equilibrium\nmatter.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 3 Dec 2020 18:47:03 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-06-30"}
