{"id":"2012.02286","submitter":"Panayiotis Moutis PhD","authors":"Panayiotis Moutis, Omid Alizadeh-Mousavi","title":"Digital Twin of Distribution Power Transformer for Real-Time Monitoring\n  of Medium Voltage from Low Voltage Measurements","comments":null,"journal-ref":"IEEE Transactions on Power Delivery (2020)","doi":"10.1109/TPWRD.2020.3017355","report-no":null,"categories":"eess.SY cs.SY","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/","abstract":"  Real-time monitoring of distribution systems has be-come necessary, due to\nthe deregulation of electricity markets and the wide deployment of distributed\nenergy resources. To monitor voltage and current at sub-cycle detail, requires,\ntypically, major investment undertaking and disruptions to the operation of the\ngrid. In this work, measurements of the low voltage (LV) side of distribution\ntransformers (T/F) are used to calculate in real time the waveforms of their\nmedium voltage (MV) sides, based on a mathematical model of said T/F. This\nmodel is, essentially, the dig-ital twin of the MV side of the T/F. The method\ncalculates T/F MV waveforms of voltage and current, and active and reactive\npower as accurately as an instrument T/F, captures all harmonics con-tent, is\nunaffected by asymmetrical loading and identifies most sys-tem faults on the MV\nside of the T/F. The digital twin method en-ables monitoring of distribution\nT/F that avoids MV instrumenta-tion, does not suffer in accuracy and may be\nreadily deployable. Field data from an actual MV-LV T/F, agree with simulation\nre-sults showcasing the efficacy of the digital twin method.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 3 Dec 2020 21:48:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-12-07"}
